Rearrangement of the Middle East
President Bush, the Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israel's Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about reaching a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into America's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the Planning Staff at the U.S. Department of State, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What was achieved in Iraq - and what the Iraqi people can now rebuild with the help of Americans - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could foster reforms and growth throughout the region.
It will take some time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East have taken hold.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam Hussein has humanitarian, security-policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the foresight of the Americans and the whole world, as well as the rapid, concentrated, and goal-oriented intervention of coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge turned out to be less severe than anticipated.
There is a need for humanitarian aid now and then, but fortunately, the announced massive crisis never materialized.
There are relatively few internally displaced persons in Iraq. The supply of food, water, and medications is generally sufficient or at least improving.
The American government has provided approximately 600 million dollars through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
Furthermore, we must restore the rule of law in Iraq.
Security is an indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work, or go back to school.
After the fall of Saddam, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and retribution.
Now it is top priority to put an end to this violence.
Furthermore, it must be the task of international troops to secure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors worsen the already fragile situation.
Long-term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures so that they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more precisely as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected, and modern Iraq possesses a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of resources to process in Iraq.
The U.S. has provided more than 2 billion dollars to support the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production will be raised to a higher level.
Long-term challenges include increasing oil production and reducing Iraq's enormous debts.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the religious, ethnic, geographical, and political divides within Iraqi society, helping to politically renew Iraq is likely the most challenging task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans—to have an intact Iraq where the law is respected and a democratic government comes into being—is no utopia, especially not considering that Iraq has a educated population and a relatively large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue following the course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have impacts on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly an external political issue that more strongly engages and polarizes public opinion than the Palestinian question.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush announced his goal of a democratic Palestinian state existing peacefully with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the USA developed a roadmap that brings us closer to this goal step by step.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent an important step in this direction.
Now the Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to move this process forward and take measures to improve the situation in order to then tackle more far-reaching issues at the negotiating table.
Finally, it cannot be allowed that terrorists spoil the peace process for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically the solution to all problems in the Middle East.
The clear and unambiguous challenge posed to us by Iran is that this country develops weapons of mass destruction and supported terrorism.
Such behavior defies the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues on this path, it will have consequences.
If, however, the country turns away from terrorism and the development of catastrophic weapons, the USA is ready to resume good relations with this country.
Similarly, the USA is willing to engage with Syria if substantial attitude changes are achieved there.
A more general issue is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
The United States tolerated for too long the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to advocate for a representative form of government.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems lead to resentments and extremism against the interests of the USA, the West, and the entire world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the partnership initiative for the Middle East, which was launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Also closed economic systems pose a threat.
As the previous "Arab Human Development Report" shows, the Arab countries of the Middle East lagged far behind other regions in terms of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
These countries have had to watch the economic boom pass them by for too long.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If one were to realize his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the USA and the Middle East within a decade, this would be a viable basis for such development.
